ba","marks":1,"options":["Substantia nigra pars compacta","Substantia nigra pars reticulata","Globus pallidus interna","Dorsal striatum","Globus pallidus externa"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn Huntington\u0027s disease, the \u003Cstrong\u003Edorsal striatum\u003C/strong\u003E (caudate nucleus and putamen) is the primary site of early neurodegeneration. Specifically, medium spiny neurons are selectively lost, leading to disrupted inhibitory output to other basal ganglia structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other regions are not primarily affected in early disease:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstantia nigra pars compacta\u003C/strong\u003E - primarily affected in Parkinson\u0027s disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstantia nigra pars reticulata\u003C/strong\u003E - affected later in disease progression\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlobus pallidus interna\u003C/strong\u003E - may be affected in later stages\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlobus pallidus externa\u003C/strong\u003E - may be affected in later stages\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe selective loss of striatal neurons results in the characteristic choreiform movements seen in Huntington\u0027s disease due to disrupted basal ganglia circuitry. As the disease progresses, neurodegeneration becomes more widespread.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Huntington\u0027s disease primarily affects medium spiny neurons in the dorsal striatum (caudate nucleus and putamen) before widespread degeneration occurs.","The selective loss of striatal neurons leads to characteristic choreiform movements due to disrupted inhibitory output to other basal ganglia structures.","The genetic mutation causing Huntington\u0027s disease involves an expanded CAG repeat in the huntingtin gene on chromosome 4."],"references":["Blumenstock S, Dudanova I. Cortical and Striatal Circuits in Huntington\u0027s Disease. Front Neurosci. 2020 Feb 6;14:82. doi: 10.3389/fnins.2020.00082. PMID: 32116525; PMCID: PMC7025546.","Ehrlich ME. Huntington\u0027s disease and the striatal medium spiny neuron: cell-autonomous and non-cell-autonomous mechanisms of disease. Neurotherapeutics. 2012 Apr;9(2):270-84. doi: 10.1007/s13311-012-0112-2. PMID: 22441874; PMCID: PMC3337013.","Balleine BW, Delgado MR, Hikosaka O. The role of the dorsal striatum in reward and decision-making. J Neurosci. 2007 Aug 1;27(31):8161-5. doi: 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.1554-07.2007. PMID: 17670959; PMCID: PMC6673072.","Morigaki R, Goto S. Striatal Vulnerability in Huntington\u0027s Disease: Neuroprotection Versus Neurotoxicity. Brain Sci. 2017 Jun 7;7(6):63. doi: 10.3390/brainsci7060063. PMID: 28590448; PMCID: PMC5483636.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60133"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16545"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60133"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T09:59:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T07:42:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9236"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74639"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"h